00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:46.890
profitability of your own

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:48.210
funds, because you have

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:49.270
put less money.

00:10:50.210 --> 00:10:51.970
We always understand this well

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:54.330
when we put the example with a housing.

00:10:54.990 --> 00:10:56.570
You buy a house and you mortgage

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:58.470
at the maximum, imagine a lot

00:10:58.470 --> 00:11:01.070
of money and the price of the house

00:11:01.070 --> 00:11:04.350
results in a year, two years,

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:07.470
whatever, and you have obtained

00:11:07.470 --> 00:11:09.450
a plus value of 100,000 euros,

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:11.690
for example, and you still put

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:12.790
very little money.

00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:14.810
The profitability of that money

00:11:14.810 --> 00:11:16.590
you put on your own funds

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:18.250
is very high.

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:18.950
Why is?

00:11:19.330 --> 00:11:20.690
Because of the leverage, thanks

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:22.850
to the financing that has allowed

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:24.470
you to make an investment

00:11:24.470 --> 00:11:25.610
in an asset with a value,

00:11:25.610 --> 00:11:27.270
but putting very little money.

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:30.590
Therefore, ROE depends on the profitability

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:32.410
on assets and how we have

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:33.830
funded ourselves.

00:11:39.630 --> 00:11:41.130
It is interesting to understand what

00:11:41.130 --> 00:11:42.430
the rotation of assets consists

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:44.670
of and how it affects profitability.

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:46.630
If we see the definition,

00:11:46.630 --> 00:11:48.290
the rotation of an asset is the

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:52.010
number of times in a period that

00:11:52.010 --> 00:11:54.150
that asset becomes sales.

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:55.610
We could do so with the entire

00:11:55.610 --> 00:11:56.790
asset or we could do so, for

00:11:56.790 --> 00:11:57.950
example, with specific items

00:11:57.950 --> 00:11:59.610
such as stocks, which are the

00:11:59.610 --> 00:12:02.490
assets that are constantly rotating.

00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:04.690
What is what happens?

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:06.390
The higher the turnover, the

00:12:06.390 --> 00:12:08.930
same amount of assets generates

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:11.210
more sales or, seen from another

00:12:11.210 --> 00:12:13.230
perspective, for the same volume

00:12:13.230 --> 00:12:14.290
of sales you would

00:12:14.290 --> 00:12:15.690
need to finance less

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:16.850
asset volume.

00:12:17.750 --> 00:12:19.030
What I want you to understand is that

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:22.110
the higher the rotation, the higher

00:12:22.110 --> 00:12:23.410
the profitability because

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:25.170
we need less assets, as we

00:12:25.170 --> 00:12:25.930
were seeing.

00:12:26.630 --> 00:12:27.970
This affects the ROE on the

00:12:27.970 --> 00:12:29.330
profitability of the asset.

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:30.730
In this formula, we see it.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:32.310
If the profitability on the asset is

00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:33.610
equal to the net profit taken by the

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:35.570
asset, if the rotation is greater

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:37.270
and we need fewer assets, because the

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:38.790
profitability is greater, right?

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:41.330
And here, look, we have it more disaggregated.

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:44.590
The ROE is equal to the margin

00:12:44.590 --> 00:12:48.030
you get for every euro you sell.

00:12:48.030 --> 00:12:49.630
How much is net profit?

00:12:49.650 --> 00:12:50.510
The more margin the more

00:12:50.510 --> 00:12:51.910
profitability, obvious.

00:12:52.730 --> 00:12:55.270
And, in addition, it depends on the rotation

00:12:55.270 --> 00:12:57.070
because the higher the rotation

00:12:57.070 --> 00:12:59.510
you will need a smaller amount

00:12:59.510 --> 00:13:01.430
of assets.

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:11.020
Cash flow is the amount

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:12.380
of cash flow that has

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:14.880
been generated in a business,

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:15.980
in a company, in an investment

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:18.180
over a period of time.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:20.740
There is a difference

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:21.780
between net profit and

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:22.600
cash flow.

00:13:23.060 --> 00:13:25.500
Net profit is calculated

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:26.960
income minus expenses, but what

00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:28.260
you have to keep in mind is that

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:30.240
income and expenses are

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:32.120
purely accountable sizes, not

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:33.180
objective sizes.

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:34.340
What do I mean by this?

00:13:34.680 --> 00:13:35.700
It depends on the rules

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:38.140
of each country, how you apply

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:39.880
them, etc.

00:13:39.940 --> 00:13:41.720
You can periodize income,

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:43.900
periodize expenses, amortise

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.780
more, less, etc.

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:46.820
Instead, cash flow is totally

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:49.120
objective, it is the treasury

00:13:49.120 --> 00:13:51.700
it has been able to generate.

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:53.480
We also need to know what the most

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:56.740
popular cash flows are and how they

00:13:56.740 --> 00:13:57.840
are calculated.

00:13:58.100 --> 00:13:59.700
In the world of finance, there

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.240
are basically two sizes of cash flow,

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:02.660
mainly, which is the free cash

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:04.720
flow, which is the free cash flow,

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:08.020
and the cash flow of the shareholders.

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:10.010
Let’s see how it is calculated.

00:14:10.210 --> 00:14:11.230
We start from the magnitude

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:12.610
of profit related, which I will not

00:14:12.610 --> 00:14:13.650
explain here in detail, but basically

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:14.910
we start from the profit

00:14:14.910 --> 00:14:17.630
and what we do is adjustments.

00:14:17.830 --> 00:14:19.630
The first thing we do is adjust

00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:22.710
it with lots that have been taken

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:24.250
into account to calculate the

00:14:24.250 --> 00:14:26.930
profit, but that really don’t

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:27.930
affect the box.

00:14:28.370 --> 00:14:29.470
The most obvious example is

00:14:29.550 --> 00:14:30.710
the amortisation.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:33.530
You when you amortise is a cost

00:14:33.530 --> 00:14:34.530
on the result account, but

00:14:34.530 --> 00:14:35.830
really the amortisation is

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:37.430
not a cash out.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:38.890
We must start with the

00:14:38.890 --> 00:14:40.970
profit and add the amortisations.

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:44.770
We also have to pay for the

00:14:44.770 --> 00:14:46.350
investments we have made over

00:14:46.350 --> 00:14:47.670
a period of time, over

00:14:47.830 --> 00:14:48.450
a year.

00:14:48.950 --> 00:14:50.790
If you make investments,

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:52.750
those investments are not

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:54.230
included in the income account.

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:56.390
They are assets you have acquired

00:14:56.390 --> 00:14:57.670
or have increased whatever.

00:14:59.090 --> 00:15:00.250
Well, because those investments

00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:01.850
do what you have less treasure.

00:15:01.950 --> 00:15:05.110
You have devoted treasury to making investments.

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:06.630
They are usually divided between

00:15:06.630 --> 00:15:10.910
investment in circulating capital,

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:12.310
working capital, operational

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:13.630
fund needs, i.e. more operational

00:15:13.990 --> 00:15:17.930
needs, and investment

00:15:17.930 --> 00:15:20.310
in fixed assets in capex.

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:23.050
We have the free cash flow

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:24.570
and the free cash flow.

00:15:24.950 --> 00:15:26.190
The free cash flow is the

00:15:26.190 --> 00:15:28.810
cash flow generated by the company

00:15:28.810 --> 00:15:30.810
without considering how we have

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:32.170
funded ourselves.

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:33.790
That is, until now we have not

00:15:33.790 --> 00:15:36.370
taken into account the entries

00:15:36.370 --> 00:15:37.870
or exits of debt, we have not taken

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:39.950
into account interest, etc.

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:41.930
Well, if we want to calculate,

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:44.870
make the final cash flow that

00:15:44.870 --> 00:15:46.710
remains for shareholders, what

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:47.970
we have to do is start with

00:15:47.970 --> 00:15:50.210
the free cash flow, add the

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:51.130
debt entries if we have

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:52.650
received debt, restate the

00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:54.950
debt amortisations and also

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:56.830
restate the interests we had

00:15:56.830 --> 00:15:57.970
to pay for those debt.

00:15:58.110 --> 00:15:59.190
The only thing that remains is the

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:00.630
cash flow of the shareholders.

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:08.120
You should understand very well what

00:16:08.120 --> 00:16:10.300
it consists of and how capitalization

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:13.500
or discounting and updating

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:15.500
of cash flows is done.

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:17.140
We start with capitalization.

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:19.120
Capital is to carry a cash flow to the

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:21.780
future, that is, to calculate how much

00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:22.840
it is worth in the future.

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:23.980
And how do we do it?

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:24.960
In this case, what we do is multiply

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:27.820
by a capitalization factor

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:29.880
that depends on the type of

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:31.520
interest we expect to generate

00:16:31.520 --> 00:16:33.660
that investment.

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:37.460
The opposite is done with capitalization

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:39.360
or with discount.

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:41.040
What we do is calculate how much

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:43.760
cash flows are worth today that

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:45.340
are predictable in the future.

00:16:46.560 --> 00:16:47.700
In this case, we do

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:48.900
not multiply, in this case

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:50.980
we do divide by a discount

00:16:50.980 --> 00:16:52.140
factor.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:54.860
We apply a discount rate.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:56.160
What you have to understand is that

00:16:56.160 --> 00:16:58.680
the discount rate depends on the

00:16:58.680 --> 00:17:01.280
expected risk in that investment.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:03.660
We also saw that we can disagree

00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:04.760
this way, it depends on the interest

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:06.800
without risk, which is the cost of

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:08.800
opportunity, and it depends on the

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:11.020
risk premium you estimate or apply

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:12.680
to that investment, to that particular

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:14.460
company.

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:17.390
This is the basis

00:17:17.390 --> 00:17:18.610
of cash flow.

00:17:19.010 --> 00:17:20.250
In this case, when we discount cash

00:17:20.250 --> 00:17:21.490
flows, what we have is a series

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:22.730
of future cash flows and we

00:17:22.730 --> 00:17:25.390
will discount them and bring them

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:26.550
to the current moment by applying

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:28.950
a rate that, as we have seen,

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:31.310
depends on the required

00:17:31.310 --> 00:17:32.370
profitability.

00:17:33.370 --> 00:17:34.990
If we perceive that it has a lot

00:17:34.990 --> 00:17:37.530
of risk, we demand a higher profitability,

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:38.950
we apply a higher rate, because

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:40.670
the current value of all those funds

00:17:40.670 --> 00:17:42.290
will be lower.

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:51.820
It is important that you understand

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:53.540
well how a company is valued, what

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:55.160
are the main methods and more.

00:17:56.100 --> 00:17:57.320
Well, basically we could say that there

00:17:57.320 --> 00:17:58.240
are three approaches.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:00.940
The first is to estimate the value

00:18:00.940 --> 00:18:02.380
of a company from the value of

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:03.380
its assets.

00:18:03.440 --> 00:18:04.700
Within this approach there

00:18:04.700 --> 00:18:05.660
are different methods, we can

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:06.940
do it in different ways, but we

00:18:06.940 --> 00:18:09.440
will not go into detail now.

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:11.980
The second would be to estimate the

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:14.660
value of a company based on

00:18:14.660 --> 00:18:16.040
the market value of other transactions

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:17.640
that have been generated or

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:19.260
what companies listed in

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:21.020
the sector are worth, etc.

00:18:21.140 --> 00:18:22.320
That is, we look at how much companies

00:18:22.320 --> 00:18:24.080
are worth that are comparable

00:18:24.080 --> 00:18:26.480
and we get some conclusions and

00:18:26.480 --> 00:18:27.320
apply it to ours.

00:18:27.460 --> 00:18:29.320
This is done with the multiple,

00:18:29.320 --> 00:18:31.060
with the comparable multiple.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:33.680
There are some that are well known, such

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:35.640
as EBITDA, for example, or as the

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:36.900
PERC, which is the Price Earning

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:38.420
Ratio.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:40.960
For example, imagine that in similar

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:42.520
transactions of companies

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:44.200
like yours, in your sector,

00:18:44.200 --> 00:18:46.680
etc., the transaction has been

00:18:46.680 --> 00:18:50.500
valued at an EBITDA of 7.

00:18:50.980 --> 00:18:52.900
Well, you will do what you will do

00:18:52.900 --> 00:18:56.140
is apply that multiple to your

00:18:56.140 --> 00:18:58.180
company and you will get the value

00:18:58.180 --> 00:18:59.060
of your company.

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:01.200
It is very easy to do.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.440
The last of the methods and the

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:07.000
most orthodox we have is cash

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:08.340
flows.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:09.880
In this case, what we do is analyze

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:11.040
the company and project

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:14.060
the cash flows that we expect

00:19:14.060 --> 00:19:15.340
that company will generate

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:16.980
in the coming years.

00:19:18.020 --> 00:19:19.680
And then we discount those cash

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:21.440
flows, bring them to the current

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.940
moment, applying it to a

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:24.800
discount rate.

00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:27.500
This discount rate depends on the risk.

00:19:27.680 --> 00:19:29.300
It is not the same thing that

00:19:29.300 --> 00:19:30.780
we are valuing, imagine, a startup

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:32.180
with a very high degree of

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:34.240
innovation and very high risk that

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:35.240
we are valuing an investment

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:37.740
because that is very stable in

00:19:37.740 --> 00:19:38.900
which we know almost to science

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:40.640
what will happen and more.

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:43.000
So we project cash flows

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.120
with expectations, etc.

00:19:45.200 --> 00:19:47.440
We discount them using a discount

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:48.720
rate that is representative

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:50.640
of the risk.
